<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-352-856  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 352 856.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  June 13 1989 v3 n23 p36(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>System 7.0: the management perspective. (The Mac Manager) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Crabb, Don.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>The emergence of the Macintosh System 7.0, though associated withfinancial and planning problems, affords managers with anexcellent opportunity to plan for the replacement of Macintoshequipment that is aging to the point where its future softwaresupport is called into question.andP;  Apple has promised that the 7.0will run on any Macintosh with 2Mbytes of RAM.andP;  But the upgradingby third-party memory board is an expensive process.andP;  Further,some of the features of the new software will only work on Mac II,SE-30, IIx and IIcx models.andP;  Ignoring the new system risksremoving a company from the loop of system support as Appleconcentrates on 7.0 and the planning for 8.0.andP;  Planning should bepredicated on the procurement of newer equipment like the SE-30and IIcx machines, so that one will have at least 4Mbytes ofmemory in planning future applications.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (product development).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (computer programs).andO;Topic:     UpgradingSystems SoftwareSupport ServicesMemory Boards-CardsEconomics of ComputingProduct Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By DON CRABBandM;System 7.0: The management perspectiveandM;By now you've probably read about the big System 7.0 announcements that Applemade at the recent Worldwide Developer's Conference in San Jose, Calif.andO;Although the technical news is interesting in its own right, the real issuesconcern how it will affect managers' lives and what plans they should make todeal with it.andM;First of all, you need to keep the System 7.0 announcements in perspective.andO;The announcements were made to developers so they could make use of the newgoodies planned for System 7.0.andP;  The fact is that System 7.0 won't even beavailable to users until sometime in the first quarter of 1990.andP;  And that'san optimistic estimate.andM;Second, Apple has promised that System 7.0 will run on any Macintosh that has2 Mbytes of RAM.andM;Think about that number.andP;  That should include even the old upgraded MacPluses in your office, as long as they have 2 Mbytes.andP;  But how many of yourolder Macintoshes fit that bill?andP;  Upgrading to 2 Mbytes using a third-partymemory board isn't cheap, costing upward of $700.andP;  And it's not alwaysreliable because the clip-on connections can come loose.andM;If you choose to upgrade the 256-Kbyte single in-line memory modules (SIMMs)in the Plus with 1-Mbyte SIMMs, then you have to go minimally to 2.5 Mbytesof total RAM.andP;  That will cost $1,000 at current Apple list prices.andP;  Multiplythis by the number of 1-Mbyte Macintoshes in your shop, and you're talkingmajor-league red ink.andP;  And keep in mind, 2.5 Mbytes won't guaranteeMultiFinder functionality.andP;  For that, you'll probably need a 4-Mbyte machine.andM;So what's the alternative?andP;  You could choose not to switch to System 7.0.andO;After all, some of the memory management and internal features of the newsoftware (like interapplication communications and virtual memory) will workonly on Mac II, SE/30, IIx and IIcx models.andM;What else do you give up by not migrating to System 7.0?andP;  Quite a lot,actually, since the list of new features is pretty long.andP;  But the real lossis probably more important than all the outline fonts, Finder enhancements,file aliasing and other niceties planned for System 7.0.andP;  And that is Apple'ssupport.andM;Apple just doesn't have unlimited support resources.andP;  Although I'd expectSystem 6.0.2 through 6.0.4 to be supported during 1990, at some point Applewill have to cut back its support to concentrate on System 7.0 and get readyfor System 8.0.andP;  If you stick with obsolete (although officially supported)System software, you will be on your own to solve future software conflicts.andM;As much as it may hurt financially, it's time to start planning for System7.0.andP;  That planning should include the cost necessary to take your 1-MbyteMacs into the 2-Mbyte and higher range.andM;Now is also a good time to think about buying SE/30 and IIcx machines with atleast 4 Mbytes of memory, since the cost of RAM installed in these models atthe factory is significantly less than if you configure it later.andP;  And whenall is said and done, a Mac Plus with up to 4 Mbytes of memory is still a MacPlus, with its older disk drive, older power supply and older screen.andM;Look on the bright side.andP;  System 7.0 is really a good excuse for coming togrips with your aging Macintosh installation.andP;  Given Apple's penchant forhardware announcements during Macworld expos, you could put off yourdecisions until after the Boston Macworld in August.andP;  Apple just might havenew hardware on tap for late '89 or early '90 that would be a better platformfor System 7.0 than current models.andP;  n</TEXT></DOC>